(In reply to comment #4)
John, the existing code in the static initialization block of PreferencesConverter class contradicts your assertion that this code was intended to be executed only by the UI thread:
    Display display = Display.getCurrent();
    if (display == null) {
        display = Display.getDefault ();
    }
The "if" statements above demonstrates that the author of the code did try to make it suitable for execution by a non UI thread.

Fixing the rest of the static initialization block code to work on an arbitrary thread is not too hard. It can be done by replacing

   FONTDATA_ARRAY_DEFAULT_DEFAULT = display.getSystemFont().getFontData();

with

   final FontData[][] fontData = new FontData[1][];
   display.syncExec(new Runnable() {
       public void run() {
           fontData[0] = Display.getCurrent().getSystemFont().getFontData();
       }
   });
   FONTDATA_ARRAY_DEFAULT_DEFAULT = fontData[0];

Although the Perforce plug-in is somewhat antiquated, it's not its fault that Eclipse 3.3 moved plug-in initialization out of the UI thread, which was the root cause of this issue.

